report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old, right-handed woman with epilepsy for the past nine years, last seizure 2002 without loss of consciousness.  Seizures are characterized by a few minutes of confusion preceded by an aura of smelling fish and hearing seagulls.
MEDICATIONS: Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is low voltage, well organized with a 10.5 to 11 Hz, 20 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background slowing.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Comparison with this patient’s previous EEGs may be valuable to localize seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:   52-year-old right-handed woman with epilepsy for 11 years. Last seizure in 2002. Seizures are characterized by an aura of smelling fish, hearing
seagulls, and a few minutes of confusion. MEDICATIONS:  None
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in lab using standard 10-20 system
of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness  there is a 10.5 Hz  50 mV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage frontal central beta activity. Very brief drowsiness is characterized  by slow rolling eye movements. Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving. Hyperventilation does not activate the record.
HR: 	80 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are similar to a previous EEG in 2005.No epileptiform  features were identified in either study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 41-year-old woman with tonic-clonic seizures x 2.  Past history of epilepsy but currently on no medications, schizophrenia, and cocaine abuse as well as benzodiazepine ingestion.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Trazodone, Seroquel, Zoloft.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 8.5 Hz, 20 V posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by symmetric, rhythmic theta.
Hyperventilation produces a small increase in theta.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving at lower and faster flash frequencies with harmonic and supraharmonic driving.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and stage I sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. If seizures are an important consideration, a repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep or using special electrodes could be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and stage I sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year-old woman with 2 episodes with loss of consciousness
lasting minutes with postictal confusion. Past history of pulmonary emboli, bipolar
disease, migraines, benzodiazepine withdrawal, demyelination changes on the 2004
MRI, cocaine and benzodiazepine dependence.
MEDICATIONS: Percocet, Valium, Lovenox, Famotidine
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at bedside using standard 10-20 ·
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. There is no hyperventilation or
photic stimulation. Previous tracings are not available for comparison.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hertz alpha rhythm
with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta. Features of drowsiness
include slow rolling eye movements and an increase in beta. Muscle artifact was picked
up in a T4 electrode throughout the entire study.
HR: : 60-70 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL No focal nor epileptiform features were observed. The
beta described above may be due to this patient's benzodiazepine exposure.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old woman with epilepsy since 2002 with an aura of stuttering, shortness of breath, headache, and postictal confusion, seizure-free for the past three months.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz, 40 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by theta activity occasionally seen in the temporal or central regions.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and does not activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.  During relaxed wakefulness, the patient had occasional episodes of unilateral twitching of the left arm without impairment of awareness.  This was not associated with a change in the EEG.
HR:  106 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  These features are similar to this patient’s previous EEG.  The twitching was not associated with an EEG stop correlate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old woman with epilepsy; last seizure four to five months ago.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 8.5 Hz, 40 to 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There is some head rocking artifact picked up in the occipital region, particularly during hyperventilation.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing a small increase in amplitude of the background.  Drowsiness is characterized by some hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing. Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving at 5 Hz and faster flash frequencies.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal awake EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  Comparison with previous EEGs may be valuable.  Previous EEGs were not available at this time.  These results are similar to this patient’s previous study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal awake EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 34-year-old woman with seizures since 1999, complex partial in type.  Her last seizure was two years ago in 2001.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote and Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standing 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was performed for only less than one minute because the patient felt uncomfortable. Photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric and well organized.  There is a 9 to 10 Hz, 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. The alpha rhythm was well attenuated with eye opening. MU rhythm was identified in the central area.  Hyperventilation was performed for less than one minute.  Post-hyperventilation the patient became drowsy with slow rolling eye movements and with attenuation of the background.  In drowsiness, posterior slowing of 4 to 5 Hz activity is seen.  The posterior occipital slowing has harmonic features with the alpha activity. Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform discharges were seen in this tracing.  The occipital slowing during drowsiness is an unusual pattern and a repeat EEG may be helpful in distinguishing between the occipital harmonic features versus a pathological pattern.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 37-year-old right-handed female with epilepsy since
2001, average 2 to 3 seizures per month. Prior to her EEG test, the
patient was noted by the tech to have lip smacking,repetitive hand
movements and confusion which lasted less than 5 minutes.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Carbatrol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG performed in the lab using standard
10-20 system of electrode placement and one lead channel of EKG. EEG
was performed with hyperventilation and photic stimulation. The EEG
was performed from wakefulness through drowsiness.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG looks
symmetric with beta activity in the frontal region and an alpha rhythm
of 8.5 to 9 Hz with 20 to 30 mV. Sleeping stages were not accomplished
in this record. In hyperventilation, there is increased amplitude
bilaterally with slowness in the frontocentral area that returns to
baseline in less than 30 seconds. Photic stimulation activates mild
driving bilaterally.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal findings or epileptiform features were
observed on this study. Based on the patient's history long-term
monitoring may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness.

report:
HISTORY: A 40-year-old right-handed woman with recurrent black out spells, seizures, and auras. Some of her seizures are described as lip-smacking with an involuntary noise. The patient is aware of the noise but cannot stop the behavior. Concomitant migraine headaches and lupus.

MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Carbatrol.
This is an outpatient EEG #10-308 recorded on March 5, 2010

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 9 Hz 40 uV alpha rhythm with a small I amount of low voltage frontocentral beta. Drowsiness is characterized by anterior spread of the alpha. Hyperventilation does not alter the record. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 60 BPM.
Impression: Normal EEG

Clinical Correlation: If further characterization of the epileptic focus is needed, additional recording is suggested.
IMPRESSION:
Impression: Normal EEG

Clinical Correlation: If further characterization of the epileptic focus is needed, additional recording is suggested

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 59-year-old male with alcohol abuse, DTs, epilepsy, hepatitis C, cirrhosis, asthma, thrombocytopenia, leukopenia, and multiple medical problems.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan and Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is performed.  This is a primarily drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is drowsy throughout much of the record.  The overall pattern is slow voltage with generous background beta and a posterior dominant rhythm of approximately 15 V, 12 Hz.  Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  In stage I sleep, there are slow rolling eye movements with diffuse beta and in stage II sleep there are spindles.
Photic stimulation elicits brief driving at intermediate flash frequencies.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These results are similar to a previous study. No focal or epileptiform features were seen in either record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 62-year-old male of unknown handedness with alcohol abuse, hepatitis C, cirrhosis, epilepsy, peripheral neuropathy, and frequent falls.
MEDICATIONS: Beta blocks, Serax, Dilantin, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In brief wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm of 30 uV with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements.  Occasional facial twitching and jerking is identified with an EEG correlate.  The patient is noted to be markedly drowsy.  Spindle activity is identified in stage II sleep.
Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is drowsy, but does elicit scant driving.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Evaluation of this patient in regards to the cause for his hypersomnolence is appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 68-year-old woman admitted for right CEA.
MEDICATIONS: Antihypertensives.  Heparin was given at 9:30 AM.
INTRODUCTION: Portable digital video EEG is performed in the OR using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The recording begins at 8:20 AM and concludes at 10:40 AM.  Incision was made at 9:07 AM.  The clamp was placed at 9:36 AM and unclamped at 10:21 and 10:23 AM.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric and well organized. After the patient is sedated and then given anesthetics, bilateral attenuation of the background with increased theta and beta activity were identified.  Significant muscle movement artifact was reduced after anesthetics were given.  The carotid was clamped at 9:36:27 without significant change in the EEG.  However, some muscle artifact is seen on the left.  The carotid was unclamped at 10:21 and 10:23 AM.  Doppler was performed at 10:37 to confirm patency and the EEG ended at 10:40.  Throughout the monitoring, no significant changes were seen on the EEG.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No significant EEG changes were identified during the operation.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old woman with epilepsy, alcohol withdrawal, seizures, hypertension, CHF, and confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, insulin, Oxcarbazepine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is reasonably well organized with a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements and attenuation of the alpha with an increase in background beta followed by theta.  The patient is noted to be confused when she is maximally alert as well as when she is drowsy.
Photic stimulation did not elicit a clear driving response.
HR:  68 BPM with occasional PVCs.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Despite the normal EEG, the patient was determined to be confused by the technologist during the study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 29-year-old woman with a history of seizure disorder starting at age two. Her last seizure was in April 2001 when she stopped her medication due to a pregnancy. Her seizures types are absence or generalized tonic-clonic seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II to III sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is symmetric and well organized.  There is a 10 Hz, 100 V posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of frontocentral beta activity.  During hyperventilation, two isolated bursts of generalized slowing were identified.  In drowsiness, there are multiple vertex sharp waves and a two small spikes were identified in the left temporal region.  Photic stimulation elicited symmetric driving.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison with previous EEGs this EEG tracing did not show 3 Hz spike wave nor poly spike slow wave discharge.  This tracing may be suggestive of maturation of the central nervous system are possibly that the patient has outgrown her seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:

MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.

Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and produces a small degree of background slowing but no spike and slow wave activity.  Photic stimulation produces a small degree of driving. The patient starts to fall asleep during photic.
HR:  90 BPM.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and through stage I sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 32-year-old woman with a history of generalized spike and slow wave activity who ran out of Topiramate for several days and had a tonic-clonic seizure.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax, oral contraceptives.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is high amplitude, well organized with a 10.5 Hz, 75 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing a handful of bursts of paroxysmal theta, but no spike and slow wave activity.  Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements.  Vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are seen in stage II sleep, as well as abundant POSTS.  There are no definite spike and slow wave discharges seen in stage II sleep.  Photic stimulation is performed following sleep and does not clearly activate the record.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  For this individual, recent EEGs have not identified generalized spike and slow wave or poly spike and slow wave activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 53-year-old woman with syncopal spells associated with headaches occurring twice a week of unknown length of time.  Patient has episodes of feeling dizzy, hypertension, asthma, emphysema, depression, anxiety, and chest pain.
MEDICATIONS: Prozac, Diltiazem, Klonopin, and Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is a one-hour EEG.  The patient experienced some of her symptoms during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is awake, alert, and interactive.  She is observed to have tremulousness of the arms and face in wakefulness without EEG change.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record with poor effort.  This increases the patient’s trembling including facial twitching and the patient is slow to respond, however, the EEG throughout the entire hyperventilation is normal.  During this one-hour EEG, the patient again experiences the arm and face trembling at 11:02.  The tech again performs testing. The patient initially has difficulty responding, but then answers questions appropriately.  The EEG remains normal with a normal awake pattern.
Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal one-hour video EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  No cardiac dysrhythmia was identified.  Consideration for a non-neurologic cause for this patient’s symptoms is appropriate at this time.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal one-hour video EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 49-year-old female with epilepsy. No other information is available.
MEDICATIONS: Phenobarbital and Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The technologist has difficulty communicating with the patient and therefore it is difficult to assess maximal wakefulness.  In maximum wakefulness, the EEG appears to be reasonably well organized with a 9 Hz, 30 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is an increase in background beta activity.  There may be an area of very subtle accentuation of beta in the right centrotemporal region.  Vertex waves are seen in stage I sleep.  POSTS are noted in stage I sleep as well.  Vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are seen in stage II sleep.  Stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR:  42 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definite focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Clinical evaluation may be helpful regarding the sinus bradycardia.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 49-year-old female with longstanding epilepsy with recent breakthrough seizures and compliance challenges.
MEDICATIONS: Doxepin, Effexor, Phenobarbital, and Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a primarily asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Much of the record includes sleep, but in wakefulness there is an 8.5 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background slowing.  In sleep, there are abundant vertex waves, K complexes, spindles and POSTS.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing an increase in the amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR:  50 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Either a repeat tracing using special electrodes or with sleep deprivation may be helpful. Alternatively, correlation with previous EEGs may be valuable. These results are similar to previous studies.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 51-year-old woman with epilepsy 17 to 18 years ago with multiple normal EEGs in the past.  This is this patient’s third EEG.  She reports back and neck pain followed by loss of consciousness with some shaking and clenching of her teeth.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax, Effexor, _________.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.   Drowsiness is characterized by increased background beta activity. There is a lot of artifact at the T1/T2 electrodes.  Hyperventilation does not activate the record, but the patient seems very sad and/or fearful during hyperventilation.  Photic stimulation is completely obscured by photoelectric artifact.
HR:  40 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness with bradycardia.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Due to the technical problems described above, this study should be repeated.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness with bradycardia.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 52-year-old woman with a history of epilepsy for 18 years, three normal EEGs, including one three months ago.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax, Effexor, Actonel.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.  The patient had her symptoms of teeth grinding during this EEG.

report:
HISTORY:

61 y.o. female with a history of seizures.




MEDICATIONS:


Topamax




SEDATION: None


TECHNIQUE:


A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.



EEG BACKGROUND:




The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.




During very drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is not captured



No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No epileptiform activity is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:


Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with fair cooperation and produces
no effect.




Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces
symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of ~60 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is a normal awake and briefly drowsy  routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic
events reported or detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:

This is a normal awake and briefly drowsy  routine EEG.




A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.



The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of
epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is a normal awake and briefly drowsy  routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic
events reported or detected.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 38-year-old woman with recurrent seizures, history of head trauma at age 21, ran out of medications and abused cocaine with subsequent seizures.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is performed.  The patient is described as exceptionally drowsy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz, 40 V posterior dominant rhythm.  Much of the drowsy record is characterized by slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm with an increase in both beta and theta.  Stage II sleep is characterized by vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  There are rare, shifting asymmetries.  The patient is intermittently alerted from stage II sleep, but subsequently drifts back to sleep.  Photic stimulation is performed with attempts to alert the patient.  There is minimal driving at faster flash frequencies and then the patient drifts back to sleep.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG primarily in sleep within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no definite focal or epileptiform features seen in this record.  Additional clinical evaluation may be helpful regarding this patient’s hypersomnolence.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG primarily in sleep within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 48-year-old woman with meningitis and migraine headaches with the appearance of epilepsy following the meningitis.  Tremors, and gait dysfunction.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with an increase in background beta.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in the amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation is reviewed with the digital video EEG.  The technologist reports that the patient is getting antsy and agitated during photic stimulation, although the audio is off.  A bilateral brief driving response is seen and there is also some head-rocking artifact.  The technologist’s notes are excellent, although there is no audio.  The patient is telling the tech that the photic stimulation is making her shake.  Reviewing the EEG, there is head-rocking artifact in the background and the tech describes the patient as having a panic attack, but there is no epileptiform activity and the patient does permit the conclusion of photic stimulation, which elicits a bilateral driving response.
HR:  114 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Of note, the patient is tachycardic at baseline and becomes panicked during photic stimulation.  Evaluation as to the cause of these symptoms may be valuable.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old woman with hypertension, obstructive sleep apnea, and seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In relaxed wakefulness and early drowsiness, there is rhythmic, 5 Hz, sharply contoured activity with a flat-top shape in the left temporal region.  This may appear in bursts lasting up to 1.5 seconds.  There is a very slight degree of variability in the activity.  Identical, 5.2 Hz activity is identified from the right in similar states.  This is also seen at the close of hyperventilation as the patient becomes drowsy.
Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving at intermediate and faster flash frequencies.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definite epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The findings described above are most compatible with a psychomotor variant.  They have the characteristic 5 Hz activity.  On the left, there is just a touch of variability in terms of actual frequency, but the identical activity is seen on the right in the same sleep state.  To further define this, a repeat study in deeper stages of sleep could be of use, however, a previous study in stage II sleep earlier this year did not identify epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
History:	80 year old woman with a history of seizures.  No reported seizures since ~ 2008.
She now reports left sided head pain.
Medications:	Tegretol, Celebrex
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 9.5-10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow
waves appear diffusely, followed by symmetric vertex waves.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
does not produce any effect.
Summary of Findings:
No stage 2 sleep
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 21-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 21-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information

report:

and facial droop.
Medications:	Depakote
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy, portable
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 11-11.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.

rate <60 bpm.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Sleep, stage 2
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 24-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. A single EKG lead demonstrates
heart rate <60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 24-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. A single EKG lead demonstrates
heart rate <60 bpm

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 16-year-old girl with new onset seizures in November 2003, and one seizure in December 2003.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is symmetric, continuous, and well organized for a subject of this age.  There is a 9 Hz, 30 to 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation does not activate the record.  Post-hyperventilation, the patient falls into light sleep, which is characterized by vertex waves, spindles, K complexes, and POSTS.  Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal awake and asleep EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  Migraine headache.  Patient requires clearance for driver's license.
This is a 26-year-old woman with epilepsy at age 9, seizure-free since November 2013.  Patient experiences rusty taste in her mouth followed by exhaustion.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  A 24-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a technically acceptable EEG with impedances under 5 kilohms.  Some head rocking artifact was noted.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9.5 hertz alpha rhythm.  Prominent temporal wicket was noted.  Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements with rhythmic central theta.  POSTS were noted in stage 1 sleep.
At the close of the record, the patient transitions to stage 2 sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.
Hyperventilation was performed with good effort and produces a small increase in amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
Heart rate 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the 4th EEG for this patient.  Previous studies were performed February 6, 2004, March 28, 2005, and May 7, 2013.  The 2013 study was normal as this study.  No epileptiform features were noted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

report:

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Plavix, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes an 11 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of frontocentral beta activity.  In drowsiness, there is a prominent increase in background theta with occasional vertex waves.   Features of stage II sleep include vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles. report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 51 year old right handed woman, with history of possible schizophrenia and/or hypertension with episodes of syncope since the age of 13, as well as episodic confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Elavil, Seroquel, Depakote, ASA, Amitriptyline, Pravastatin, Ranitidine
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm. The patient is quite drowsy, transitioning from wakefulness into drowsiness and then as she starts to transition into stage 2 sleep there is spontaneous arousal. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude and a small amount of slowing. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 78bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no epileptiform features identified. The transitions in and out of sleep with bursts of sleep occur even during photic stimulation may occur in the context of sleep deprivation. It may also be seen in an individual who is sleepy or any other cause.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 35-year-old woman with epilepsy for the past two years after head trauma.  The seizures begin with hand shaking and loss of consciousness, convulsive activity followed by postictal confusion.  Seizures triggered by a fall in the shower.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a well-organized background with a 10 Hz symmetric, reactive posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is temporal wicket activity identified.  The wicket activity on the left is slightly higher amplitude and it is slightly irritative in its nature, but there is no definite spike or slow wave activity.  As the patient reaches deeper stages of sleep, there are vertex waves and POSTS, but deeper stages of sleep are not sustained and the patient intermittently arouses from sleep. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is relatively drowsy and does not activate the record.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There is no definite epileptiform activity, although there is some suspicious activity underlying what is likely a normal variant.  To clarify this, a repeat study with more prolonged sleep would be helpful to determine if in fact there is underlying left temporal sharp activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 35-year-old woman with post-traumatic epilepsy for the past two years.  Last seizure occurred four months ago.  Seizures begin with focal motor with secondary generalization.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a well organized 11 Hz, 15 to 20 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there are intermittent wicket spikes identified more from the left than the right temporal regions, which disappear in stage II sleep.  Stage II sleep is characterized by vertex waves and spindles.  There is also the occurrence of benign sleep transience in this patient, as well as vertex sharp waves.
Photic stimulation activates the record at higher flash frequencies to some degree.
HR:  74 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The wicket spike activity disappears in stage II sleep, which signifies a benign variant of EEG changes. A sleep deprived EEG would be useful in order to identify latent epileptiform activity in the temporal areas.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:

There is a 9Hz, 15 <DV posterior dominant alpha rhythm, with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 20-year-old woman with a history of seizure disorder, hydrocephalus with a shunt in the left occipital area.  Patient has been seizure-free for over five years and is being evaluated to come off of medications.
MEDICATIONS: Phenobarbital and birth control pills.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is continuous and symmetric. There is a 10 Hz, 25 V posterior dominant alpha rhythm, which is well attenuated with eyes opened.  There is an increased amount of diffuse beta activity.  The amplitude increased in the left frontal and temporal areas and is consistent with a breach rhythm.  Hyperventilation slightly increased the amplitude of the background.  Post-hyperventilation, the patient became drowsy, which is characterized by increased theta and beta activity. Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.  Photic stimulation elicits driving, as well as LAMBDA activity.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The increased amplitude in the left frontal and temporal areas is consistent with a breach rhythm and is due to the previous procedure of a shunt. No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  LAMBDA activity is a normal variant.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If clinically indicated, a repeat EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 48-year-old male with epilepsy since age seven; last seizure in July 2003.
MEDICATIONS: Carbamazepine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage I sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric and well organized with a 10 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation increased the background slowing.  Following hyperventilation, the patient fell into stage I sleep, which is identified by vertex waves. Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits sub and supraharmonic driving.
HR:  80 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 51-year-old male with epilepsy since age 7.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Pravachol, and Benadryl.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 9.5 Hz, 30 to 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background beta with vertex waves.  Spindles are seen in stage II sleep.  In this broad-chested, heavyset male, who is recorded sitting up, there are multiple arousals from sleep with some snore identified in wakefulness.  Hyperventilation is associated with a small increase in background slowing.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is drifting off to sleep, but does elicit scant driving at faster frequencies.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is the second normal EEG for this individual.  The first was in 2004.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  Of note, in the last EEG, the patient had harmonic and subharmonic driving, which were not seen today.  This may be due to the fact that the patient was falling asleep in photic stimulation.  Given the patient’s history of seizures during sleep and the snoring and arousals from sleep identified here, perhaps a polysomnogram should be considered.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

None

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.

A heart rate of 66 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.

This is a normal drowsy and asleep	routine EEG.	There are no clinical or electrographic events reported or detected.

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 41-year-old woman with a seizure disorder and depression. The patient states she has had increased seizures since the beginning of this month in August 2009. MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Topamax, and Paxil.
INTRODUCTION: This video EEG is performed in the laboratory using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hypoventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background EEG is symmetric continuous and fairly well-organized. The background EEG is with high amplitude of brain activity. After adjusting the sensitivity, clearly well-organized posterior dominant 9 Hz, 50-75 mcV alpha rhythm can be seen. This alpha rhythm is well-attenuated with eyes opened. There is a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity. Hypoventilation did not change the background significantly. No sleeping stages were achieved during this tracing. Photic stimulation created a driving pattern. No abnormal discharge.
Heart rate 60 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness with high amplitude background.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal findings, no abnormal discharges were seen in this tracing. Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. The very high voltage of brain wave activity on the EEG background can be rarely seen in normal subjects. If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness with high amplitude background.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 29-year-old woman who underwent surgery with a BIER block in the right arm and began to have involuntary shuttering of the shoulders.
MEDICATIONS: Valium and Benadryl.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The shoulder movements occurred whenever the patient relaxed, but would disappear whenever she paid attention.  Symptoms were marked at first, and she received a small dose of benzodiazepines.  The patient received an infusion of normal saline and then an infusion of benzodiazepines in this record for these symptoms.  She complained of occasional focal sternal chest pain during the study.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is awake with a 9.5 to 10 Hz, 40 to 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  The patient had involuntary shuttering, which did not produce a great deal of artifact in the EEG.  The EEG remained interpretable throughout.  She received an infusion of saline, which did not particularly help the symptoms.  She was more focused on her chest wall discomfort.  The patient subsequently received 1 mg of Valium, which made her somewhat drowsy and the symptoms disappeared considerably. Vertex waves were seen in stage I sleep.
Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving with at times supraharmonic driving.
HR:  56 to 64 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  There was no EEG signature noted for this patient’s jerking events.  Of note, the administration of benzodiazepines did increase the beta activity in the background.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
HISTORY:

25 y.o. male with a history of seizures since

childhood, last recurring 3 days ago, characterized by hands


cramping and being aware but unable to communicate, biting lips,

and postictal confusion. He is referred for routine EEG for

evaluation. He reported to the technician that he is not taking


his medication correctly.


MEDICATIONS:


Current Outpatient Prescriptions:

phenytoin (DILANTIN) 100 mg ER capsule, Take  by mouth 3 times

daily.



SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:




A 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the

International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a


NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record and

included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.



EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a

mixture of alpha and a moderate amount of bifrontal beta


activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.

Wakefulness is characterized by a symmetric and reactive 12 Hertz


posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which attenuates symmetrically

with eye opening.


During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and


fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm, and diffuse

background slowing are seen.




Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with

synchronous and symmetric vertex waves, sleep spindles and


K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.



No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.


EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No epileptiform activity is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180

seconds with good cooperation and produces no effect.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21


flashes per second (fps) does not produce any EEG changes. Note

that patient was asleep during part of the stimulation.



EVENTS:


There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during

this study.


HEART RATE:


A heart rate of 54 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no

clinical or electrographic events reported or detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.


A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of

epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no

clinical or electrographic events reported or detected.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 44-year-old woman with history of seizures since childhood, now transferred from Episcopal because of a seizure during a stress test and now having recurrent seizures of unresponsiveness.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while awake and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Continuous spike wave detection, as well as seizure detection software, nurses events, patient's alarm events were all used to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient has normal frontal central beta.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness, stage I, stage II, and deeper stages of sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
Abnormal discharges:  None.
Patient events:  The patient had an event at 7:26 in the morning.  She pressed the alarm, laid in bed, and became unresponsive to any verbal or motor commands.  She continued to be unresponsive for about 3 minutes, after which the doctor came in and tested her.  She started crying and appeared to be slow to answer commands, but finally ended up answering commands.  She continued crying during this event.  During the entire event there was no abnormal EEG findings and remained as a normal awake EEG.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  The patient's event in which she was unresponsive had no EEG correlate.  As such, it is consistent with the diagnosis of nonepileptic psychogenic event.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 43-year-old, right-handed male transferred from an outside hospital with a tonic-clonic seizure with a somewhat abnormal CSF, but normal MRI.  Evaluated for meningitis.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Acyclovir, and Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 10.5 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  There is a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There is sharply contoured, almost rhythmic theta activity identified in the temporal regions left greater than right. This is accentuated by hyperventilation.  It has some of the stereotypic morphologies of a normal variant, but the frequency ranges from 3.6 to 7.1 and occurs in brief paroxysmal bursts.  The patient seems to be very drowsy, drifting off into stage I sleep with vertex waves.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered outside the range of normal due to:
The rhythmic temporal theta activity, which does not have the characteristic frequencies of a normal variant.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: While the activity described above is not specifically epileptiform in nature, it renders this EEG abnormal.  Additional recording may be important to determine if this activity improves over time, or may be associated with underlying epileptiform activity.  Of note, the patient was excessively drowsy and had difficulty completing hyperventilation.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered outside the range of normal due to The rhythmic temporal theta activity, which does not have the characteristic frequencies of a normal variant.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This  is a 56-year-old  male with right-handed  weakness  and aphasia, a feeling as if he is not speaking right, and he is weak for 15 minutes.  Evaluate for complex partial epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Nexium, aspirin, Atenolol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital  video  EEG is performed  in the lab  using standard  10-20 system  of  electrode  placement  with  one  channel  of  EKG.  Photic  stimulation  was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF  THE  RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a well organized 9Hz, posterior dominant rhythm.  The activity on the left is higher amplitude than the right. Features of drowsiness include rhythmic background theta.  Vertex waves are identified in stage I sleep.  Multiple spontaneous  arousals to and from stage I sleep are observed. Photic stimulation elicits a bilateral driving response, which is symmetric.
On one or two occasions, as the patient transitions to and from sleep, there is a suggestion of disruption of faster frequency activity on the right in comparison to the left.
HR:  66BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There  is an amplitude  asymmetry  identified, with the left being higher than the right, an unanticipated finding for an individual with  a right hemiparesis  and aphasia.   There are also one or two bursts of slowing referable  to the right hemisphere raising the possibility that there may be a process in that hemisphere.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal.

report:
History:	30 year old woman with a history of epilepsy since 17 years of age, who continues
to have 3-4 seizures per week.
Medications:	Depakote (patient reports non-compliance)
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 8.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Fast alpha variant is frequently noted.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-
25Hz activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is
observed.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear
diffusely, followed by symmetric vertex waves.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair effort, and produces no effect.  Stepped
photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at multiple
flash rates.  A single EKG lead demonstrates a heart rate of ~ 60 bpm.
Summary of Findings:
No stage 2 sleep
Beta, excessive
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2
sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide
additional information. Excess beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as
benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2
sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide
additional information. Excess beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as
benzodiazepines or barbiturates

Heart rate 90 bpm.

report: HISTORY: 31 y.o. At time it appears slightly irregular in a single electrode.  IMPRESSION: This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events reported or detected.  CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG. Please note the EKG abnormality.   A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events reported or detected.

characterize her epileptiform activity is advised.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 34 year-old woman who had had problems with her knees
buckling for the past 5 years. Requires a cane. Since February 2008, she has been
having nocturnal seizures, 3 times per night. These seizures are described as loss of
consciousness with shaking and twitching followed by headache, bipolar disease (not
clear how she could lose consciousness during a seizure when she is already asleep).
MEDICATIONS: Trileptal, Valium, Darvocet, Ability
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in lab using standard 10-20 system
of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This was a 1 hour study.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 9-Hz 30 mV posterior
dominant rhythm. There is a scant amount of background theta observed.
Hyperventilation does not significantly activate the record. Drowsiness is characterized
by slow rolling eye movements. The patient has some eyebrow twitching. The
technologist has an EMG channel for this. During awake EEG, the patient demonstrates
facial twitching. The technologist asked the patient "Is this your typical seizure?" The
patient answered yes, this is her typical seizure. The video demonstrates a little facial
twitching which produces artifact and the EEG demonstrates a normal awake pattern.
The facial twitching occurs later on in the record. Features of drowsiness include
attenuation of the alpha with rhythmic background slowing. Posts are observed. Photic
stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. The clinical event
recorded was not associated with epileptiform activity. In addition, bilateral motor
activity was noted. This is compatible with a nonepileptic seizure.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 29 year old male admitted with recurrent seizures over the past 3 weeks characterized by headache,  chest pain, dizziness. Multiple seizures this morning treated with Ativan. Past history of MVA with loss of consciousness 10 years ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan
INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Patient is awake.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is an 11 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.
During this EEG the patient had a seizure. This was at 10-9-06 2006. He is lying comfortably with  a normal awake pattern. This is followed by jerking, hiccupping, and head moving from side to side. Asynchronous arm movements are noted, a little bit more so on the left arm. He turns
his head to the left, and he bounces back and forth. During the seizure a well-defined alpha
rhythm can be identified. As he rocks his head to the left, artifact is picked up on some of the scalp electrodes, but the alpha rhythm can still be seen despite the fact that he is moving about. The behavior after 43 seconds and the EEG demonstrates a normal pattern. Of note, he starts rocking his head to the right and looks to the left at the end of the event. The technologist calls the patient. He is unresponsive despite a normal awake EEG. Another event occurs at 10:10:09. He receives Ativan for the second behavior, which is not sustained. The resident comes in and examines the patient. The patient makes eye contact with the resident during the examination. By the close of the EEG he remains awake but appears more comfortable.
HR:	54-96 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The 2 behaviors observed were not associated with epileptiform activity. In addition, they had behavioral characteristics of a nonepileptic seizure.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 64-year-old woman with previous evaluation for nonepileptic seizures, depression, and anxiety.

INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient had multiple behavioral events for which she was able to push the button.  In the overnight recording, she had some problems with electrode artifact.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amounts of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.

Epileptiform detections:  None.

Electrographic seizures:  None.

Events:  Multiple practice push button were noted.  In addition, behavioral events were noted at 9:56 a.m., 12:39 p.m., 3:20 p.m., 8:45 a.m., and another on the morning of the 30th at 9:09.  Although, there was electrode artifact for the events on the evening of the 29th and the morning of the 30th, no epileptiform activity was noted for any of these events and all were associated with an otherwise normal EEG, despite some movement artifact.

Seizure semiology for 9:56 a.m. nodding and blinking. Similar behavioral changes were noted at 12:39 p.m. and at 3:20 p.m.  The seizure at 8:45 begins with nodding and blinking, and then jiggling from side to side.  The patient is with the nurse at the bedside.  The nurse is examining the patient who is responsive to the nurses intervention, although she is not speaking and does not appear to have recalled the event.

The event at 9:09 on the morning of the 30th was characterized by amnesia. The patient stated that she did not recall the physician, had not seen her before, although she was otherwise able to lie down new memories and asked appropriate questions.

Heart rate 72 bpm.

IMPRESSION:  This 4-day continuous video EEG monitoring session was remarkable for:
1. No epileptiform discharges of any nature.
2. An otherwise normal background.
3. Multiple different behavioral spells, sometimes with staring, sometimes with psychomotor slowing, sometimes with nodding and blinking, but never with epileptiform activity, despite the clear change in patient's sensorium.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are congruent with the previous EEG monitoring, which did not identify an epileptiform characteristic to this patient's events.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This 4-day continuous video EEG monitoring session was remarkable for 1. No epileptiform discharges of any nature. 2. An otherwise normal background. 3. Multiple different behavioral spells, sometimes with staring, sometimes with psychomotor slowing, sometimes with nodding and blinking, but never with epileptiform activity, despite the clear change in patient's sensorium.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 64-year-old woman, previously evaluated at Drexel for nonepileptic seizures, abnormal MRI, recurrent events and anxiety, evaluate for seizures.  Patient reports that i if she tactile stimulation of the scalp, produces drops.  She also is aware of events with tremulousness and stress-related seizures.

INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG, seizure and spike detection software.

MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, topiramate, others.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:
October 27 to October 28
Background:  In wakefulness, the background includes a well-organized 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.
Epileptiform Detections:  None.
Patient Events:  There are 3 events at 6:51, 3:53 and 4:35.  The patient pushes the button for all of the events with the exception of 1 event when the nurse was present at 6:51.  She stares off into space, is verbally unresponsive, and does not identify a code word.  In the 1st event, she stares off into space and is poorly responsive followed by some chewing movements.  She is able to follow some commands during that event.  In the other 2 events, she demonstrates tapping movements of the right hand.  For all 3 events, the EEG demonstrates a normal background.

Heart rate 60 bpm.

INTERVAL IMPRESSION AND CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This 1st 24 hours of video EEG monitoring was remarkable for a normal background in wakefulness through stage II sleep, but with 3 events without an EEG change.  The patient demonstrated impairment of awareness with the events suggesting that these events may be part of this patient's repetitive of anxiety-related seizures (nonepileptic seizures).

October 28 to October 29, 2914: During this section of the record, the patient experienced multiple nonepileptic seizures at times: 8:45, 9:48, 4:12 p.m., 6:27 p.m., 7 p.m., 8 p.m., 10:16 p.m., and midnight.

Background:  In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a symmetric reactive 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTs.

Interictal Epileptiform Detections:  None.

Pushbutton Events:  There are 8 push buttons, and event that occurred while the patient was unhooked. The patient described that tactile stimulation of her scalp produces the events that she experiences.  The events are experienced by the patient as being different but she is able to push the button for all events.  She is unresponsive.  She may moan, grimace and demonstrate automatisms in the right hand.  She is responsive during the events and while examined by the physician for the 8:47 a.m. event, follows commands, taking a deep breath and participating with the physical exam.  She does not recall the code word for any of the events.  She describes the events as feeling to her as if they are much different, Some of them feel to her as if she is just dropping out.  She is aware that tactile stimulation of the scalp can produce the events.

Normal EEG was  associated with all of these events.
Heart rate 66 bpm.

IMPRESSION:  This 2nd 24 hours of video EEG monitoring was remarkable for:
1. Multiple events without an EEG signature but with alteration in the patient's mental status.
2. A normal background.

MEDICATIONS: Propecia, Fluconazole.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed   in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement  with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and Photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.

50 to 70 meg with prominent eye movement artifact such as lateral rectus artifact. In addition, there is mu activity and temporal wicket. In hyperventilation and in a handful of occasions there is a suggestion of an underlying sharp wave in the left temporal region. Unfortunately this is the same area as remarkable for significant eye movement artifact and wicket, and some of the activity described above is clearly wicket. Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements. Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained. Photic simulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:	60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are multiple sharply contoured normal variants or artifacts including wicket and eye artifact. No definitive epileptiform features are observed. A repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep is advised.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 37 year old right handed female with new onset tonoclonic seizures beginning April of 2009. The seizures occur in the context of stress and depression.

MEDICATIONS: None

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, there is generous beta activity noted in the background. There seems to be an artifact picked up at T5. Wicket activity is identified bilaterally and is more prominent on the left. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta. Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved. Photic stimulation is performed as the patient is starting to drift off into sleep, and there is no significant
driving response.

HR: 78 bpm

IMPRESSION: This EEG is remarkable for:
1. Excess beta.
2. A normal variant; wicket; which is more prominent on the left.
3. Some technical issues with the placement of the T3 and T5 electrodes.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: If this individual is thought to have new onset epilepsy rather than panic attacks, a follow-up study in the lab capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested. The presence of the excess beta may be seen in the context of anxiety and stress, which would certainly be present for any individual attempting to have an EEG with 3 small boys. Please contact the lab if needed to reschedule or repeat the EEG with sleep or even 24 hours of home EEG monitoring.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is remarkable for 1. Excess beta. 2. A normal variant; wicket; which is more prominent on the left. 3. Some technical issues with the placement of the T3 and T5 electrodes.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 42-year-old woman with previous left temporal bleed, tonic-clonic seizures.  Baseline left-sided weakness.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Lamictal, Ativan, trazodone.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20 minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm with generous diffuse beta.  Supra harmonic alpha rhythm is noted on some occasions at twice the frequency of the baseline alpha rhythm.
Hyperventilation produces a small increase in amplitude.
Photic stimulation produces vigorous bilateral driving.  During photic stimulation, there is a slight amplitude asymmetry, slightly higher amplitude on the left.  There also seems to be an accentuation of faster frequency activity from the left during photic stimulation.
Heart rate 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an unusual, but not pathological EEG.  It is considered within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The alpha harmonic, present bilaterally is a normal variant.  The prominent driving response is again a normal phenomenon as is the beta frequency activity.
The slightly more vigorous supra harmonic driving noted on the left, ipsilateral to the heterotopic tissue is not necessarily pathological and may be considered within the broad range of normal possibilities of photic response.
Previous EEGs were not available for comparison.  No sharp waves or spikes were noted today.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an unusual, but not pathological EEG.  It is considered within normal limits.

report:

10/08/2012-10/09/2012

report:
History:	46 year old woman with a history of seizures since 17 year old.
Medications:	Depakote, Seroquel, Zoloft, Albuterol
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by low amplitude 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is present.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha
rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair effort and produces no effect.  Stepped
photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce any effect.
Summary of Findings:
Beta, excessive
No stage 2 sleep
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 21-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information. Excess beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect,
such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 21-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information. Excess beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect,
such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates
