CLINICAL HISTORY:  27 year old right handed woman with seizures versus nonepileptic seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Zonisamide, Topamax.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.   Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz 50 mV alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage frontal central beta. Brief fragments of stage I sleep include vertex waves, followed by arousal. Photic stimulation is performed as the patient is starting to transition in and out of sleep and does not significantly activate the record. Hyperventilation produces a small increase in amplitude of the background.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were observed.  Sleep deprivation might produce the changes described above.
LONG TERM MONITORING - # 12-72 – 06/19/2012 to 06/20/2012
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient recalls 3 episodes.  The first is on the 19th at noon where she felt a little startled.  The second was at 10 p.m. where she felt a mini aura characterized by tingling sensation on her face.  She did not recall an episode at 5:25, although she did push the button for a tingling sensation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Random wakefulness and sleep includes a well-organized 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low-voltage frontocentral beta activity.
Event time 11:22:  There is a burst of rhythmic left temporal theta delta with frequency evolution.  This is 5 seconds in duration.  There is no push button at that time.
Event time 5:25:20 p.m.:   A burst of rhythmic theta, frequency was subtle, frequency evolution lasting only 3 seconds.  Thirty seconds later the patient reports the mini-aura which she no longer recalled.
Event time 9:58 p.m.  No abnormalities on the EEG were identified at that time.
Event time10:25 a.m.:  There was another burst lasting 4 seconds in duration in the morning on the 20th which is similar to the 2 prior bursts.   No clinical features were recalled.
HR:    60 bpm
INTERVAL IMPRESSION:  There are 3 bursts of rhythmic theta from the left temporal region with frequency evolution.  These are concerning as a potential interictal epileptiform discharge.  They may also be clinically significant with the mini-auras that the patient experienced.
LONG TERM MONITORING - # 12- 72 – 06/20/2012 TO 06/21/2012
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a well defined 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  This is a sleep deprived record.  Around 10:00 p.m. the patient seems to be trying to stay up.  The EEG demonstrates small EPOCHS where the patient seems to be drowsy.   Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, K-complexes, and spindles. The data is reviewed for the clinical symptoms that the patient experienced, but no epileptiform features are identified.
HR:    66 bpm
LONG TERM MONITORING - # 12-72 – 06/21/2012 TO 06/22/2012
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  The patient reported an aura at 8 p.m. on the 21st.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  Around 8 p.m., the patient is noted to transition in and out of stage 2 sleep, waking up and falling back asleep.  Fragments of deeper stages of sleep are noted overnight.
No electrographic seizures were identified.  The seizure and spike detector did not identify any other epileptiform abnormalities.
Event time 11:55:  The patient pushes the button at 11:56:12 stating that she feels as if she is about to have an aura.  She puts her hand to her chest and later appears to be tearful.  The EEG is awake at this time.  No epileptiform features were noted.   For her 8:00 p.m. the patient reported symptoms that her throat was closing with the seizure.

HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Continuous digital video EEG monitoring session was remarkable for 3 bursts of rhythmic, paroxysmal theta, all less than 4 seconds in duration, but with frequency evolution.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient's clinical symptoms did not appear to be associated with well-defined epileptiform abnormalities.  On one day, however, there were discharges which appear epileptiform in nature.  While this patient did not have any of her larger spells with head turning, a feeling as if her throat was closing or impairment of awareness, this record does not exclude a diagnosis and clinically, diagnosis may be considered.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

37 year old man with seizures since 2005
keppra, dilantin, flexeril, prilosec, albuterol, restoril, zoloft None
Routine, awake & drowsy
International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1fT2 electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic




Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening. Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions. During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.

No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.

Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect. Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at intermediate flash rates.

Summary of Findings:
Alpha rhythm, normal

report:
DATE OF STUDY: 05/24/16

RECORDING ENVIRONMENT: outpatient


EEG TYPE: 40-60 min (1 hr 2 min), awake and asleep





HISTORY:

 a 32 y.o. female with a history of convulsions referred for routine EEG for
characterization of seizures.



MEDICATIONS:


levETIRAcetam (KEPPRA) 500 mg tablet, Take 3 tablets by mouth every 12 hours for 360 days.


SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:

A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:







The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 9.5 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.




During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with synchronous and symmetric POSTS, vertex
waves, sleep spindles and K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.




No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.


EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:


No epileptiform activity is present.


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with good cooperation and produces
bilaterally synchronous slow waves.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce
any EEG changes.



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 54 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is a normal awake and asleep 1-hour EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.




CLINICAL CORRELATION:




This is a normal awake and asleep 1-hour EEG.

A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is a normal awake and asleep 1-hour EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.

report:
DATE OF STUDY: 06/21/16

RECORDING ENVIRONMENT: inpatient


EEG TYPE: 20-40 min, awake and drowsy




HISTORY:

a 32 y.o. female with a history of seizures since about 24 years old, referred for
routine EEG for characterization of seizures and management of seizure exacerbation.



MEDICATIONS: Keppra 1500 mg q12h


S/p load of fosphenytoin


SEDATION: Ativan 2 mg IV



TECHNIQUE:

A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a  technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG.




EEG BACKGROUND:







The waking background is characterized by the presence of a well organized symmetric mixture of
alpha and beta frequencies, with a symmetric and reactive 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm
(PDR). The normal anterior-to-posterior gradient of frequency and amplitude is present.




During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is not captured



No generalized slowing is present.

No focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

None



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.


EVENTS:


6/21/2016 at 09:36

CLINICAL: the patient is lying quietly in bed with eyes closed. She opens her eyes, blinks a few
times, then turns onto her left side and stiffens her body, arching her back. There are some
superimposed irregular jerks.


EEG: there are no EEG changes, other than movement artifact. An awake background with a
sustained posterior dominant rhythm is seen intermittently. There is no postictal attenuation or
asymmetry of background rhythms.


EKG: heart rate increases from baseline 78 bpm to ictal 96 bpm



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 50 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is an essentially normal awake and drowsy  routine EEG. An episode of body stiffening with back
arching has no EEG correlate and is most consistent with a nonepileptic behavioral event.




CLINICAL CORRELATION:




This is an essentially normal awake and drowsy routine EEG. An episode of body stiffening with back
arching has no EEG correlate and is most consistent with a nonepileptic behavioral event.


A normal routine EEG does not support or exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.



Attending Epileptologist: 

I have personally reviewed this study, and this report represents my findings and conclusions.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is an essentially normal awake and drowsy  routine EEG. An episode of body stiffening with back
arching has no EEG correlate and is most consistent with a nonepileptic behavioral event.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  35 year old right handed woman with history of epilepsy since the age of 16, who now presents with 2 generalized tonic clonic seizures.  Of note, the patient ran out of Klonopin about a week ago and she did not take her Keppra and Zonisamide.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Lovenox, Keppra, Klonopin, Zoloft, Haldol, Terazosin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well formed and regulated 9-10 Hz that attenuates with eye opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  Excess beta is present throughout the recording.  During drowsiness the posterior dominant rhythm attenuates voltages decreased, diffuse beta appears.  Wickets are present as well during drowsy and awake.  No epileptiform discharges are present.  There is no focal slowing. Hyperventilation produces mild diffuse slowing. Photic stimulation results in symmetric occipital driving.
FINDINGS:
No stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
Excess beta.
IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy EEG.  Excess beta could be due to medications, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, but stage II sleep was not recorded.  If clinical suspicion for seizures persist, a repeat study with sleep, stage II, may be of benefit.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not exclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not exclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  35 year old right handed woman with seizures since age 16, now refractory to medications.
MEDICATIONS:  Valproic Acid, Lovenox, Depakote, Keppra, Klonopin, Zoloft, Haldol, Terazosin
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long-term EEG was performed for 24 hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Continuous spike wave detection as well as seizure detection software as well as nurses' notes and patient's alarms were used to review the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and stage 1, stage 2 and deeper stages of sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
EVENTS:  The patient had 2 events in this recording similar to the ones in the previous day.  The first one occurred at 8:10:43 p.m. and the second one occurred at 11:47 p.m.  Both of them, the body had irregular shaking for minutes with no response to verbal or motor commands.  The patient had no EEG correlate during this time despite being unconscious.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG with 2 episodes of nonepileptic events.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The 2 episodes described above had no EEG correlate, as such it is consistent with nonepileptic seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG with 2 episodes of nonepileptic events.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 41-year-old woman status post aneurysm coil July 2012.  The patient subsequently developed epilepsy 1 month later with repetitive tonic-clonic seizures with loss of consciousness and confusion. Currently seizure-free.
MEDICATIONS:  Topiramate, Zyrtec, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was deferred.  Photic stimulation was completed.  This is a technically acceptable routine 20-minute EEG aside from T1 to 2 electrode impedances which were slightly higher than 5 kiloOhms.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements and attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  The patient quickly drops into stage 2 sleep with vertex waves and spindles.
Hyperventilation did not activate the record.
Photic stimulation elicited a bilateral driving response.
Heart rate 78 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Previous EEGs are not available for comparison at this time. No focal or epileptiform features were noted in this record. This is patients second normal EEG.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity.  A brief epoch of
waveforms seen during typical REM sleep is captured.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces mild diffuse
symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.  A single EKG lead demonstrates
premature QRS complexes, QRS complexes that change appearance and occasional up to 1.5
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Sleep, stage 2
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. A brief epoch that could represent
REM sleep is captured.  REM sleep is not typically seen in a spot/ routine EEG - please correlate
with an underlying sleep disorder.  A single EKG lead demonstrates premature QRS complexes,
QRS complexes that change appearance and occasional up to 1.5 second inter-QRS pauses.
IMPRESSION:

MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION:  20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This was an awake and asleep record.

There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Microsleeps are noted with brief dropouts of the alpha rhythm and very brief epochs of stage 1 and stage 2 sleep with vertex waves and K complexes.
Hyperventilation did not activate the record.  The patient was dropping in and out of stage 2 sleep during photic stimulation
Heart rate:  72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is one of many EEGs for this individual who completed previous routine and 3 days of continuous video EEG monitoring.  None of the studies have demonstrated epileptiform activity. Microsleeps were noted today, may be due to sleep deprivation or an underlying sleep disturbance.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and stage 2 sleep.

report:
LENGTH OF EEG:  21 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 45-year-old woman who presents with a large pulmonary embolism, scheduled for an embolectomy on 6/27/2013.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilaudid, oxycodone, trazodone, and heparin.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Stepped-photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated very low amplitude 11 to 11.5 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During drowsiness the background voltage is increased and the amount of theta increases as well.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Stepped-photic stimulation results in symmetric occipital driving with multiple flash frequencies.  Excess diffuse beta is captured.
FINDINGS:
Low voltage.
No stage 2 sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
Excess beta.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy 21-minute EEG.  Excess beta could be secondary to the medication effect.  The lack of epileptiform discharges noted on a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy 21-minute EEG.  Excess beta could be secondary to the medication effect.  The lack of epileptiform discharges noted on a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 53-year-old woman with 8-month history of recurrent episodes of deja vu, olfactory paroxysms and a bitter taste in her mouth, history of reflux, hypertension, and migraine.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra ? Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous digital video EEG monitoring was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Seizure and spike detection software was utilized.  The patient was able to push the monitor and recorded 12 events with olfactory symptoms and a bitter taste in her mouth, but none with impairment of awareness.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG was well organized with symmetric reactive 10 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with POSTS noted in sleep.  The patient appears to have difficulty getting to sleep and was up throughout much of the night, but brief stage II sleep was noted.
INTERICTAL EPILEPTIFORM DETECTIONS:  None.
ELECTROGRAPHIC SEIZURES:  None.
PUSH BUTTONS:  times  11:11, 11:47, 12:39, 01:50, 02:59, 04:20, 04:30, 05:02, 06:13, 08:18, 11:13 p.m.  Although one of these included a practice  pushbutton, all others were for the patient's clinical symptoms.  All demonstrated a normal awake pattern.
HEART RATE 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This first 24 hours of continuous video EEG monitoring was remarkable for:
A normal awake and sleep pattern.
The absence of epileptiform activity.
Multiple push button events for symptoms without impairment of awareness, which did not carry an EEG scalp correlate
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This first 24 hours of continuous video EEG monitoring was remarkable for A normal awake and sleep pattern

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 53-year-old right-handed woman for EEG monitoring with recurrent episodes of olfactory disturbance or bitter taste in her mouth, history of migraine, seizure medications on hold.
MEDICATIONS:  Topiramate and Keppra on hold
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG and seizure and spike detection software.  This was a technically acceptable 24-hour recording.
EVENTS: During the EEG monitoring session, the patient had 19 push button spells for a funny taste or smell.  These included 7:41, 8:04, 9:25, 9:33, 10:16, 10:30, 10:37, 11:11, 11:32, 11:44, 1:11, 3:05, 3:54, 6:59, 8:50, 10:09, 11:03, 3:05, and 7 p.m.  The EEG demonstrated a normal pattern with a heart rate of a 70-80 bpm.
INTERICTAL EEG:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  The patient has somewhat disrupted sleep, but did get to sleep a little earlier on the night of the 17th.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with POSTS noted in stage 1 sleep.  Brief stage 2 sleep includes spindles and K complexes.
EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY: NONE
Heart rate 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This 2nd day of continuous video EEG monitoring was remarkable for:
Normal awake and a sleep record, although there was limited sleep.
Nineteen push button events without EEG change  on the final day of recording
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No evidence of epilepsy was found.  These findings were discussed with the patient and a diagnosis of nonepileptic seizures was reviewed with the patient, which she understood at the conclusion of her EEG monitoring.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This 2nd day of continuous video EEG monitoring was remarkable for Normal awake and a sleep record, although there was limited sleep. Nineteen push button events without EEG change  on the final day of recording

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 40-year-old woman with past history of stroke, migraine headaches, recurrent confusional spells, and evaluate for epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:  Topiramate, gabapentin, Fioricet, Percocet, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  A 40-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is a technically satisfactory EEG with most impedances below 5 kilo-ohms.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 10.5 hertz 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Abundant stage II sleep is captured with vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, POSTS, and beta spindles, which are harmonic of her typical 13-15 hertz spindle.  Hyperventilation elicited scant slowing of the record, but photic stimulation elicited a vigorous bilateral driving.
Heart rate 78 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal 40-minute EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a second normal EEG for this adult.  If this patient found to have frequent seizures, an ambulatory monitor or other tests may be helpful to characterize her spells.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal 40-minute EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 57-year-old woman with a 2 week history of episodes of paralysis.  She states that she can't talk or move.  Her eyes are open and she is aware of what is going on.  The spells last 10 minute.  Past history of asthma, dysthymia, DVT, cocaine addiction and diabetes.
MEDICATIONS:  Lasix, Flonase, Proventil, HydroDIURIL, insulin, Neurontin, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  Hyperventilation was deferred.  This was a routine 20 minute outpatient EEG.  It is technically satisfactory, although there was a fair amount of muscle and movement artifact noted.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  In wakefulness, there is a fair amount of chew artifact.  Lambda was noted.
As the patient drifts off to sleep there is an increase in beta.  There is the appearance of posteriorly predominant slowing as well as electrocardiogram artifact and as the patient becomes drowsy there is a bit more head rocking, but a suggestion of slowing in the right occipital region relative to the left.
Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.
HEART RATE 60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is likely within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were noted.  There were no major abnormalities and the asymmetry noted in the occipital regions may represent head rocking artifact as the patient drifts off to sleep.  If additional information is needed, a more prolonged sleep EEG may be of value.  In addition, if this patient is thought to have sleep paralysis, a formal sleep study may be helpful.  Alternatively, consider a 1 hour EEG in the lab with a muscle monitor to look for evidence of reduced muscle tone in states other REM sleep.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This EEG is likely within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 28-year-old male with childhood epilepsy seizure-free between ages 9 and 25, breakthrough seizure after alcohol ingestion.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel  EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a technically satisfactory EEG, although impedance in the T1-T2 electrodes are just above 5 kilohms.  There are no previous EEGs available for comparison.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Scant theta is noted in the background.  The patient is very drowsy with transitions in and out of stage 1 sleep with slow rolling eye movements.
In drowsiness, there are a handful of bursts of shifting slowing as well as a synchronous eye artifact.
Hyperventilation produces a small increase in theta.  Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting off to sleep, but did elicit a driving response.
Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is at the limits of normal for an adult of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No sharp waves or spikes were noted in this record.  This patient demonstrates a great deal of eye artifact, but no definitive epileptiform features.  This seems to be a very drowsy individual.  To more completely characterize this patient's epilepsy, a followup study capturing more extensive sleep may be obtained.  The eye artifact described above is not a pathological finding.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This EEG is at the limits of normal for an adult of this age.

None

IMPRESSION

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is an 81-year-old woman for EEG monitoring for possible hypothermic protocol.  Temp 34.6.
MEDICATIONS:  Propofol, fentanyl, and midazolam.
INTRODUCTION:  Intraoperative monitoring was recorded from 7:21 a.m. until 9:48 a.m.  This recording was performed in anticipation of possible utilization of hypothermic protocol.  Physician was available for remote review and physician remote review was employed for 50 minutes, from 8:10 until 9 a.m.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG begins with the patient somewhat sedated.  The patient is awake with a posterior dominant rhythm with a generous beta, theta, and occasional shifting slowing.  An 8.3 Hz alpha rhythm was noted.  At 7:42, anesthetic medications are employed and EEG demonstrates an increase in background slowing.
Anesthetic medications are adjusted from 9 a.m. and EEG recording is intermittently pause for Bovie and other maneuvers.  The EEG demonstrates an intermittently discontinuous pattern.
Shortly after 9 a.m., the surgeon changes the operative strategy and EEG monitoring was not required.  The team signed out of the OR at 9:48, at which point there was a discontinuous pattern, compatible with anesthesia.
HEART RATE 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Limited intraoperative monitoring demonstrated symmetric, relatively normal awake baseline and the appearance of a burst suppression pattern with the utilization of anesthesia.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Limited intraoperative monitoring demonstrated symmetric, relatively normal awake baseline and the appearance of a burst suppression pattern with the utilization of anesthesia

INTRODUCTION:  A 1-hour digital video EEG was performed in the lab, using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This EEG is technically limited by T6 electrode artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz, 50 mV posterior dominant rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Generous frontocentral beta activity was identified.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background theta with vertex waves and spindles in stage 2 sleep.

report:
History:	29 year old man with a history of seizures.
Medications:	keppra, topamax, ativan, flexeril
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 11Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with poor cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at
multiple flash rates.  HR 60
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
No stage 2 sleep
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 21-minute EEG, awake, drowsy. The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine
EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 21-minute EEG, awake, drowsy. The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine
EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 29-year-old male with 8-year history of epilepsy. Describes tonic-colonic seizures with incontinence, tongue biting, and respiratory arrest.  Seizures in July and November 2014.  Patient reports sensations throughout his body on the day before his seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Topamax.
INTRODUCTION:  One hour digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  This is a technically acceptable record with impedances under 5 kilohms for most electrodes.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is an 11 hertz, 80 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm.  Posterior slow waves of youth were noted.  Patient appears to have been sleep deprived and rapidly transitions in and out of stage 2 sleep.
Photic stimulation:  The patient was in stage 2 sleep during photic stimulation.  Despite this, a driving response was noted at 15 hertz.
Hyperventilation did not activate the record.
Heart rate 78 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were noted.  This was the 3rd normal EEG for this adult.  It did capture extensive stage 2 sleep.  If this individual continues to have frequent seizures, alternative techniques to capture epileptiform activity or a seizure may be considered.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

was admitted to the epilepsy monitoring unit for 4 days with continuous video EEG  (3
days 95951).  This was an elective EMU monitoring session for characterization of symptoms.



The interictal EEG is characterized by  A normal, posterior dominant rhythm.



The patient was weaned off Keppra over the course of heradmission.No other medication changes
were made during the hospitalization.



We recommend she continue to see a psychiatrist.  She and her wife are happy to do so.  With
careful review of the symptoms, the family feels that most of the symptoms have been due to
overmedication and that the patient was much improved by medication reduction.  Therefore,
neither patient nor family was eager to prolonged hospitalization or tried to elicit a nonepileptic
seizure.  The family was encouraged to speak up with practitioners to avoid overmedication.  The

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 30-year-old woman with history of seizures since age 17, 3 per month, treated with multiple medications.  Anxiety and substance abuse.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, topiramate, and Xanax.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous digital video EEG monitoring was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This recording session was terminated early when the patient insisted on smoking in the room, unplugged the equipment and demanded to leave.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:
Background:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness was characterized by slow rolling eye movements with POSTS.  The patient was relatively drowsy.  Stage 2 sleep included spindles. Recording was discontinued at 4:51 PM by the patient.
Event: 12:10:49 PM  The patient was awake.  Her partner was in the room.  She had an episode of speech arrest with head turning away from the clinicians. EEG demonstrated an awake pattern. No epileptiform features were noted.  After the partner left, the patient was noted to cry and then drifted off to sleep by 12:37.
Seizures: none
Epileptiform Activity: none
Heart rate 96 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal 6-hour EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the 4th normal EEG for this adult.  No epileptiform features were noted.  At least 1 clinical event was captured, although it was not seizure with motor activity.  This individual is thought to have epilepsy, alternative management strategies may be considered.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal 6-hour EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 69-year-old woman with a left carotid stenosis.
MEDICATIONS:  Unknown.
INTRODUCTION:  Twenty-minute digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 11 Hz alpha rhythm.  The patient is quite drowsy throughout much of the EEG and drifts off to stage 2 sleep.  In the transition, slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm was noted.
Photic stimulation did not significantly activate the record.
Heart rate irregular at 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal 20-minute routine EEG without focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings will be used for the patient's operative baseline.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal 20-minute routine EEG without focal slowing.

report:
History:	74 year old man who will undergo a right carotid artery stenting today.
Medications:	N/A
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy, portable
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and
subtemporal chain, awake, drowsy, asleep
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 11-12 Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is present.  During drowsiness, the background
slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm
attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate
voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  A single EKG lead demonstrates
intermittent premature QRS complexes.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Sleep, stage 2
Beta, excessive
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 23- minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. Excessive beta activity could be
secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 23- minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. Excessive beta activity could be
secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates

report:
History:	35 year old who presents with recurrent staring episodes.
Medications:	Depakote, Fioricet, Topamax - all used for headaches Sedation:
EEG Type:	Continuous (inpatient), 24 hrs
Technique:		International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep
Continuous bedside video-EEG monitoring
Continuous EEG monitoring was performed for -15 hours from -5 pm on 9/2/2014 till - 8 am on 9/3/2014. Nursing-initiated event buttons were correlated with clinical behavior. Ongoing raw EEG data was reviewed at least twice daily by the EEG team for detection of seizures and changes in EEG patterns.  All automatically detected events were reviewed in detail by the ICU monitoring technician and the attending neurologist. The Getman spike and seizure detection algorithm (Stellate) was used to screen the EEG in real time for electrographic seizures and interictal epileptiform discharges.
# Push button events
Description of pushbutton events
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions. Diffuse excess beta activity is captured.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.  Several epochs of REM sleep are captured.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  No typical events are captured. Summary   of   Findings:
Beta, excessive
No electrographic seizures
Interpretation:
This is a normal 15-hour continuous video EEG monitoring.  No typical events were captured. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 36-year-old man with a 12-year history of epilepsy, last seizure at 1-2 years ago, here for follow up EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra 500 mg, HCTZ, thyroid
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  It is a routine 20-minute EEG with acceptable impedances, aside from the T1-T2 electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The patient is very drowsy throughout the EEG, but in maximal wakefulness there is 11 Hz alpha rhythm.  As he becomes drowsy, there is prominent theta within the frontal regions.  The patient was feeling asleep during photic stimulation, which still elicited harmonic and super-harmonic photic driving.  At the close of photic stimulation, patient was transitioning into stage 2 sleep.  Heart rate is 96 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through sleep, very drowsy patient.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are noted.  If indicated, a follow up study with photic stimulation in wakefulness may be considered.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through sleep, very drowsy patient.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 36-year-old male with epilepsy, seizure-free for the last 1-2 years.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, thyroid medicine.
INTRODUCTION:  1 hour digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This is a technically satisfactory 1-hour EEG with most impedances less than 5 kilo-ohms.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  In drowsiness, rhythmic temporal theta was noted.  Extended sleep was attempted.  The patient was noted to have snore artifact, and POSTs but sustained stage II sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles was not achieved.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal 1-hour EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were noted.  This is the 2nd normal EEG for this patient who has been seizure-free for 1-2 years.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal 1-hour EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 67-year-old woman with advanced dementia, failure to thrive, prior refusal to eat, cervical myelopathy, status post fusion, admitted with recurrent seizures characterized by twitching of the mouth and right hand.
MEDICATIONS:  Phenytoin, Vimpat, benzodiazepines, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The recording began several hours after the patient has been treated for recurrent focal seizures with little in the way of a clear change in mental status.
 04/07/2015 to 04/08/2015
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  During the early hours of the record, the background EEG is diffusely slow.  There are intermittent rhythmic bursts of theta noted from the left temporal region, but these do not have clear build up and are not associated with clear change in the patient's level of consciousness.  As the patient drifts off to sleep, the EEG is markedly slow and featureless.
In this section of the record, no clinical seizures were recorded.  Practice push buttons were noted.  The patient had an episode of vocalization without clear clinical correlate.
Heart rate:  90 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Day #1, April 7th to 8th:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was remarkable for:
A markedly slow pattern.
Some bursts of rhythmic slowing noted in the initial sections of the record without clinical change.
Markedly slow background.
04/08/2015 to 04/09/2015
MEDICATIONS: Phenytoin, Vimpat, others.
INTRODUCTION:  During this section of the record, the patient was increasingly arousable and interactive, although essentially nonverbal.  No clinical seizures were noted.
Background:  The overall background is markedly slow, lacking the typical morphologies of wakefulness or sleep for this adult.  Intermittent more rhythmic theta was noted from the left temporal region, but not in sustained bursts. Additional recording on the morning of April 9th demonstrate a patient, who is more awake.  The background EEG remained markedly slow, heart rate 90 bpm.
Epileptiform activity: None
Clinical seizures none.
Electrographic seizures none.
Sleep record:  Markedly slow pattern with at times, rhythmic theta.
Heart rate:  90 bpm.
Impression:  This 2 day, continuous video EEG monitoring session was remarkable for:
Markedly slow background.
Relatively featureless pattern, lacking in a normal wave forms expected in wakefulness and sleep for an adult of this age.
Bursts of rhythmic theta noted from the left temporal region, most remarkable on the 7th, seen much on the 8th and not present on the 9th.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In this individual with recurrent seizures on the morning of the 7th, this EEG shows resolution of a recurrent seizure pattern for this patient with a clinical diagnosis of focal motor status epilepticus.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  Day #1, April 7th to 8th:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was remarkable for A markedly slow pattern. Some bursts of rhythmic slowing noted in the initial sections of the record without clinical change. Markedly slow background. 04/08/2015 to 04/09/2015

No clinical seizures were noted. Background:  The overall background is markedly slow, lacking the typical morphologies of wakefulness or sleep for this adult. The background EEG remained markedly slow, heart rate 90 bpm. Epileptiform activity: None

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 21-year-old young man with history of questionable seizure during sleep and intermittent dizziness and left-sided numbness.  He was studied to rule out seizures.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  A routine 21-channel EEG was performed utilizing a standard 10-20 system of electrode placement along with hyperventilation, photic stimulation, and EKG monitoring.  In the awake resting background reveals a moderate amount of 20-30 microvolt amplitude, 9-11 Hz activity posteriorly, which attenuates with eye opening.  Low voltage frontocentral beta-activity was seen, which was bilaterally symmetric.  Moderate amount of muscle eye blink and prominent EKG artifact was seen.  The patient appeared drowsy during much of the record with attenuation of posterior rhythmic activity and diminished beta activity along with increased low to medium amplitude frontocentral 4-6 Hz theta.  Positive occipital sharp transients of sleep were noted (POSTs) followed by progression to stage 2 sleep with vertex waves, central sleep spindles, and occasional K-complexes.  Hyperventilation produced no significant activation of the record.  Photic stimulation produced symmetric occipital driving.  EKG monitor showed normal sinus rhythm at 62 per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake, drowsy, and sleep EEG and normal EEG, exclude clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  If clinically indicated, more prolonged recording or ambulatory EEG may provide further diagnostic information.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal awake, drowsy, and sleep EEG and normal EEG, exclude clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  If clinically indicated, more prolonged recording or ambulatory EEG may provide further diagnostic information

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 25-year-old woman with 2-year history of epilepsy.  Patient also suffers from anxiety attacks.  Has episodes with loss of consciousness, confusion, shaking.  Past history of conversion disorder, depression, and bipolar illness.  This is a repeat, 1-hour EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, Klonopin, Risperdal, Prozac, others.
INTRODUCTION:  A 1-hour digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is a technically satisfactory EEG with impedances under 5 kilo ohms.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm, symmetric and reactive to eye opening with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by an increase in beta.  Central Mu activity was likely seen but testing was not performed to confirm this.  Photic stimulation elicited brief driving.  Hyperventilation did not significantly activate the record.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal 1-hour EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this EEG.  Previous studies were not available at this time for comparison.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal 1-hour EEG.

report:
History:	26 year old woman with a history of seizures since 2012.
Medications:	LAMICTAL,RISPERDAL,KLONOPIN,PROZAC,TOPAMAX
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Extended, 40-60 min
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 12Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
During brief stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces mild diffuse
symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Sleep, stage 2, brief
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 1-hour EEG, awake, drowsy, and briefly asleep.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is a NORMAL 1-hour EEG, awake, drowsy, and briefly asleep

INTRODUCTION:  One hour digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.  Hyperventilation was deferred.  The patient was quite drowsy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The overall EEG is low voltage, but there is a glimpse of a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background theta and an increase in frontal central beta.  Vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles were noted in stage II sleep.
Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
Heart rate:  75 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal 1-hour EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the 2nd normal EEG for this adult.  If epilepsy is an important consideration and ambulatory record, capturing this patient's clinical symptoms may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal 1-hour EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 22-year-old male who developed epilepsy in 2006, previously evaluated, with 7 prior ambulatory EEG recordings .  Prior EEGS demonstrated 3 to 4 Hz spike and wave activity and many staring spells without an EEG correlate.  Now, the patient is aware of events with staring and blinking.
MEDICATIONS:  Zarontin, levetiracetam.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient was able to push the button for all events.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:
February 23rd to 24th:
Background:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with abundant low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness was characterized by increase in beta.  Vertex waves, K complexes, spindles were noted in stage 2 sleep.   Sleep is fragmented and patient is primarily in lighter sleep states.
Epileptiform seizures:  None.
Pushbuttons:  Practice pushbuttons only.
Interictal epileptiform detections:  In stage 2 sleep, there is rare dyshormia noted at 4:04 and 4:27 with a question of underlying 4 Hz spike and wave superimposed upon sleep morphology with spindle.
Heart rate 78-108 BPM
IMPRESSION:  Day 1:  Remarkable for:
No events.
Dyshormia:  the only brief epileptiform activity noted only in sleep.
February 24rd to 25th:
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Zarontin, medications in reduction.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring continues for 22-year-old male with staring spells.  The patient had multiple push buttons for staring spells during this 24-hour section.
Background:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Abundant stage 2 sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  Of note, sleep was relatively disrupted on the 1st day, but the patient seemed to be having more extensive stage 2 sleep early in the morning on the 24th.  In stage 2 sleep, occasional beta spindles were noted.  REM sleep was noted during multiple sections of the overnight recording with multiple spontaneous brief arousals from REM sleep.  There may have been some snore artifact noted at other times, but the arousals from REM sleep were not associated with epileptiform activity or significant snoring that could be detected by the recording strategy employed.
Epileptiform seizures:  None.
Pushbuttons:  On the 24th, there were 17 push button events.  Two of these were practice pushbuttons.  These events span primarily around 12:19 p.m., but standard time from 12:07 p.m. until 1:57 p.m., and then again 3:31, 4:32, and 7:18:45.  The patient is communicative and conversing with the nurse during the blinking spells.  He is awake during all of them.  After sometime, the nursing staff does not enter for every spell, but the patient can be seen clearly involved and engaged in activities and in some cases talking on the phone.  No epileptiform features were identified with the push buttons.  The EEG consistently demonstrates a normal awake pattern, although he does have some increase in heart rate.  For the 1:57 p.m. event, the patient does demonstrate a clear change in heart rate with a somewhat irregular heart rate at the end.
Epileptiform Detections:  Rare epileptiform detections were noted exclusively in sleep in this section of the record.  They are primarily seen in stage 2 sleep and include frontally predominant 2.5 to 4 Hz spike and wave activity as well as a isolated spike and wave activity.  With review using an average reference, some of the isolated spikes demonstrate a maximum between FC and F3.
Heart rate 60 to 90 to 130 BPM bpm
IMPRESSION:  This 48 hour EEG monitoring session was remarkable for:
An interictal EEG, which demonstrates spike and wave and slow spike and wave activity, at this time, exclusively in sleep, similar to the previous EEG monitoring from 2006 to 2010.
Some spike and wave activity demonstrates L FC maximum.
Multiple episodes of blinking, involuntary blinking noted and wakefulness.  No EEG change noted. Patient is awake and alert for all
On rare occasions, an irregular heart rate.
Disrupted sleep with multiple arousals from REM sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were noted in association with the patient staring and blinking.  The irregular heart rate was also noted without clinical symptoms and referral for Cardiology consultation may be considered.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 52-year-old male with HIV/AIDS, admitted with recurrent episodes of syncope, the patient recalls feeling dizzy then falling with 2- to 3-minute loss of consciousness preceded by blurry vision, increasing headaches, and forgetfulness.
MEDICATIONS:  Retrovirals, Bactrim, aspirin, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Routine 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This EEG captures wakefulness through sleep.  It is a technically acceptable EEG with most impedances below 5 kilohms.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The overall EEG is low voltage, but there is a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  The patient transitions rapidly between wakefulness and stage 2 sleep with vertex waves, spindles, and POSTS.
Hyperventilation does not significantly activate the record.
Heart rate: 60 to 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow up study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 63-year-old woman with history of aneurysm,  now with intermittent shaking spells, headaches, and feeling as if she has a lightening bolt in her head followed by a difficulty moving arm and leg.
MEDICATIONS:  Unknown.
INTRODUCTION:  A 36 minute routine video EEG was performed in the lab/ using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was completed.  The patient experienced shaking spells during the EEG, which were unlike her usual spells.  During which the patient experienced multiple tremulous spells, which she states are unlike her usual seizures.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  In drowsiness, there is intermittent left temporal focal slowing with brief bursts of theta/delta
Photic stimulation was performed early in the record.  The patient reports that photic stimulation made her feel extremely uncomfortable.  It produced a normal driving response, but the patient stopped the photic stimulation because she felt unwell.  During the 19 hertz stimulation, she had an episode of shaking of the legs, unassociated with a change in the EEG.  Afterwards, she felt that she was going to throw up as is typical with 1 of her spells.  During the EEG, the patient felt that she was going to be sick at 3:27.  She did not vomit.  By 3:28, she continues to feel unwell and cannot catch her breath, but the EEG shows a normal awake pattern.
At 3:29, the patient is crying.  At 3:32, the patient reports pain and is consoled by the nurse.
The patient continues to feel unwell, but the EEG demonstrates normal awake pattern.  Patient is able to follow commands.  At 3:40, the patient has an experience where she cannot close her eyes.  EEG demonstrates a normal awake pattern.  The physician enters at 3:43.  EEG continues to demonstrate a normal awake pattern.  At 3:50, the patient is crying and again the EEG demonstrates a normal awake pattern.
Heart rate: 96 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This 36 minute EEG was remarkable for:
Multiple somatic complaints without EEG change. Normal EEG during the spells
Intermittent Left temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  EEG monitoring will follow to look for potential epileptiform seizures.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  This 36 minute EEG was remarkable for Multiple somatic complaints without EEG change. Normal EEG during the spells
Intermittent Left temporal focal slowing.

report:
History:	42 year old man with a history of seizures.
Medications:	Neurontin, Pantoprazole, Zocor, Zyprexa, Flomax
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Patient remains awake throughout the entire recording.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce any effect.  There is
nearly continuous eye blink artifact.

No epileptiform discharges
No stage 2 sleep
Artifact, eye movement, eye blinking

This is a NORMAL awake-only 30-minute EEG.  No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage
2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide
additional information. There is nearly continuous eye blink artifact.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL awake-only 30-minute EEG.  No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage
2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide
additional information. There is nearly continuous eye blink artifact

report:
HISTORY:

43 y.o. MAN WITH PMHX OF SZS.  PT STATES HAD BEEN SZ FREE SEVERAL
YRS THEN HAD ONE LAST SUMMER. AURA OF FEELING JITTERY, JUMPY,  WEAK, THEN GTC.
SMALL ONE PER PT.  PER PT AIDE PT GETTING EEG BECAUSE PSYCHIATRIST WANTS MEDS
EVAL. FOLLOW UP EEG 5-23-16



MEDICATIONS:

GABAPENTIN,CETIRIZINE,TAMSULOSIN

SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:

A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG, HV and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.






During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.




Sleep is not captured


No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No epileptiform activity is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with good cooperation and produces
no effect.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce
any EEG changes.



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 66 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is a normal awake and drowsy  routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:


This is a normal awake and drowsy  routine EEG.

A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is a normal awake and drowsy  routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.

report:
History:	58 year old female who had an episode of generalized shaking and preserved
consciousness.
Medications:	Ativan, Cardizem, Norvasc, Tiotropium, Heparin
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Continuous (inpt, video), 24 hrs, portable
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep
Continuous bedside video-EEG monitoring
Continuous EEG monitoring was performed for 22 hours from 1/21/2015 till 1/22/2015.   Nursing-

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 70-year-old woman, admitted to the hospital on April 10, 2015.  Multiple metastases to brain/dura/scalp admitted with unresponsiveness and seizure characterized by eyes looking left, tongue biting, and foaming at the mouth.  Prolonged status epilepticus on the morning of the 10th.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, phenytoin, vancomycin, piperacillin, phenytoin, warfarin, methimazole, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous digital video EEG monitoring was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  The patient was intubated and poorly responsive throughout the monitoring session.
April 10th to April 11th:
This section of the EEG begins after the patient has been treated for status epilepticus and was intubated and unresponsive.  The first 24 hours of the record demonstrate diffusely slow pattern with mixed theta delta and occasional arousals with muscle artifact  Some sections of the record demonstrate a bit more arrhythmic theta than the others.
There is a bit more theta noted on the morning of April 11, 2015.
Electrographic seizures:  None.
Clinical events:  None.
Epileptiform Detections:  None significant.
April 11, 2015 to April 12, 2015:
Medications, norepinephrine, vancomycin, piperacillin, phenytoin, warfarin, methimazole, Ativan, and others.
Introduction:  EEG monitoring continues.  No clinical seizures were noted.
Background:  The background demonstrates a diffusely slow pattern with more of a pattern of theta and delta.  Occasional spontaneous arousals were noted.
On the 12th, there were some sections of the record noted with more rhythmic, higher amplitude delta.
There are also some triphasic waves noted.
Seizures:  None.
Epileptiform Detections:  There are some subtly defined midline vertex sharp waves noted.  These differ from normal sleep morphologies.  They do not evolve, but during some sections of the record, they are somewhat more prominent than others.
Heart rate: irregular, 60 to 90 bpm.
April 12, 2015 to April 13, 2015:  During this section of the record, no clinical seizures were noted.  The patient remained intubated and unresponsive.
Medications, norepinephrine, vancomycin, piperacillin, phenytoin, warfarin, methimazole,
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG continued to demonstrate a markedly slow pattern.  Intermittent rhythmic delta activity was noted as were triphasic waves.  Occasional spontaneous arousals were noted.
Electrographic seizures:  None.
Interictal sharp waves or spikes:  Vertex sharp waves can be identified using various montages.  There is a higher amplitude sharp wave  maximum at FZ.  In some sections of the record, it is more prominent than others.
Heart rate:  irregular, 70 to 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This 72-hour continuous video EEG monitoring session was remarkable for,
Markedly slow background with intermittent arousals.
Absence of normal waveforms, awake and asleep.
An emerging F7 sharp wave noted, which was monitored for an extended period of time, which did not evolve into clinical or electrographic seizures.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings were discussed with the clinical team.  The emerging sharp wave noted at FZ is thought to correlate with a metastasis in that same region in this individual with multiple cerebral metastases.  No electrographic or clinical seizures were recorded throughout the patient's prolonged recording.
__________________________
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  This 72-hour continuous video EEG monitoring session was remarkable for,
Markedly slow background with intermittent arousals. Absence of normal waveforms, awake and asleep. An emerging F7 sharp wave noted, which was monitored for an extended period of time, which did not evolve into clinical or electrographic seizures.

The emerging sharp wave noted at FZ is thought to correlate with a metastasis in that same region in this individual with multiple cerebral metastases.  No electrographic or clinical seizures were recorded throughout the patient's prolonged recording.

History:	35  yo male who had a new onset SZ on Tuesday night. Pt said he fell over, + body
shaking, - tongue bite, - incont., - head trauma, lasting a few mins. Afterwards pt was
very confused, he could hear people talking to him, but could not respond…
Medications:	None
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a low amplitude, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse, frontally predominant 5-10uV, 18-25Hz activity is also seen.
During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more
prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce any effect.  HR was
Summary of Findings:
Excessive fast
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2
sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide
additional information. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as
benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:

sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide
additional information. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as
benzodiazepines or barbiturates

report:
HISTORY:

35 y.o. male with a history of hemophilia,

HCV, and possible seizures vs convulsive syncope referred for


routine EEG for evaluation of paroxysmal events.


MEDICATIONS:


aminocaproic acid (AMICAR) 250 mg/mL (25 %) solution,

levETIRAcetam (KEPPRA) 500 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth 2

times daily. Start one at bed for three days and then one twice a


day


SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:

A 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the


International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a




NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record and

included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.



EEG BACKGROUND:


The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a

mixture of low amplitude alpha and a moderate amount of bifrontal

beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior

gradient.  Wakefulness is characterized by a symmetric and


reactive 10.5 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which

attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.



During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and

fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm, and diffuse

background slowing are seen.



Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with


synchronous and symmetric vertex waves and sleep spindles. Slow

wave sleep was not captured.


No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:


No epileptiform activity is present.


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180

seconds with good cooperation and produces mild diffuse symmetric

background slowing.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21


flashes per second (fps) produces bilateral symmetric photic

driving, which is a normal finding.



EVENTS:


There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during

this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 72 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no


clinical or electrographic events reported or detected.


CLINICAL CORRELATION:

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.


Of note this the 2nd normal routine EEG for this patient.

A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of


epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no


clinical or electrographic events reported or detected.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 37-year-old woman with epilepsy since age 8, admitted on the 19th with chest pain. The patient subsequently had a seizure on presentation to the ED.
MEDICATIONS:  Topiramate.
I NTRODUCTION: A 22-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed, but hyperventilation was deferred.  This is a technically acceptable record with most impedances below 5 kilohms with the exception of the T1-T2 electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9.5 hertz, 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background theta followed by POSTs and spindles in stage 2 sleep. Snore artifact was sometimes noted. Nor may also have disrupted the patient's sleep.
Photic stimulation was performed while the patient had been in stage 2 sleep and minimal activates the record.
Heart rate: 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified. No previous EEGs are available at this time for comparison. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a followup study may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 41-year-old woman with new-onset seizures, September 2014, characterized by screaming, shaking, tongue biting, and amnesia. This event followed alcohol and cocaine ingestion, and Xanax use.
MEDICATIONS: Xanax, Singulair, Flonase, Prilosec, and others.
INTRODUCTION: One-hour digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. Mu activity was identified, but testing was not performed to confirm this. There is a small amount of underlying theta in the posterior regions bilaterally. Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements and an increase in beta as well as attenuation of the alpha rhythm. Rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness appears in the transition in and out of sleep. Stage 2 sleep was characterized by spindles. There may be underlying snore arousals. Hyperventilation produced an increase in theta.
Photic stimulation was performed as the patient was falling asleep. There was a photic driving response noted.  In addition, rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness with a characteristic 5 Hz activity was noted during photic stimulation.
Heart rate 60 to 78 bpm.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and a brief stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness is a normal variant.  No definitive epileptiform features were noted.  The patient appears to be quite drowsy with frequent arousals and snoring. Clinical evaluation may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and a brief stage 2 sleep.

Description:

symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over

Sleep, stage 2

Beta, excessive
Interpretation:

secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.

This was a  technically satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG.   DAY 1 (1/26/2016, 11:24 - 1/27/2016, 06:00)  MEDICATIONS: Gabapentin is stopped  EEG BACKGROUND: The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is characterized by a symmetric and reactive 11 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.   Prominent lambda waves are seen in wakefulness.  During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.   Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with synchronous and symmetric POSTS, vertex waves, sleep spindles and K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was captured and normal.  No generalized slowing is present. No focal slowing is present.   EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY: No epileptiform activity is present.  OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):  None  ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: not performed  EVENTS: There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.  HEART RATE: A heart rate in the 60s-80s bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.  IMPRESSION: This is a normal long term video EEG. There are no clinical or electrographic events reported or detected.  CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is a normal awake and asleep long term EEG. No clinical or electrographic events were reported or detected.  Reading attending:     -----------------------------------------------------------------  DAY 2 (1/27/2016, 06:00 - 1/28/2016, 06:00)  MEDICATIONS: gabapentin still held  BACKGROUND: No change  GENERALIZED SLOWING: No change  FOCAL SLOWING: No change  PAROXSYMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM): None  SPORADIC EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY: None  ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: 1/27/2016 at 10:28 Hyperventilation is performed for 3 minutes and produces mild background slowing  1/27/2016 at 10:36 Stepped photic stimulation in intervals from 1-21 flashes per second produced bilateral symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.  Additionally, patient is sleep deprived until 1/28/2016 03:00.  EVENTS:  (1) DATE AND TIME:  1/27/2016 at 20:06 EVENT TYPE: Event of unclear etiology CLINICAL: Patient complains of feeling "hot and tingly." Nurse tests her at 20:10 and she is A&Ox3, following commands.  On rounds the next morning, the patient notes that these symptoms are not her typical habitual events. EEG: No ictal epileptic EEG correlate is present DURATION: ~8 min POSTICTAL CHANGES:  No change in cerebral rhythms EKG: unchanged HR in single EKG lead  EKG: A single EKG lead captured a heart rate in the 60s-80s  DAY 2 IMPRESSION & CLINICAL CORRELATION This is a normal awake and asleep long term EEG.  The episode of feeling "hot and tingly" had no clinical correlate; given the duration and nature of the complaint, it is unlikely to represent a seizure.   Reading attending:     -----------------------------------------------------------------  DAY 3 (1/28/2016, 06:00 - 1/28/2016, 13:25)  EMEDICATIONS: gabapentin still held  BACKGROUND: No change  GENERALIZED SLOWING: No change  FOCAL SLOWING: No change  PAROXSYMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM): None  SPORADIC EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY: None  EVENTS: No clinical or electrographic events reported or detected  EKG: A single EKG lead captured a heart rate in the 60s-70s   DAY 3 IMPRESSION & CLINICAL CORRELATION  Normal EEG  Reading attending:     -----------------------------------------------------------------  FINAL IMPRESSION & CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal video EEG.  The patient's typical habitual events were not captured and no conclusion can definitively be made as to whether or not they represent seizures.  One episode of feeling "hot and tingly" that lasted several minutes was captured on 1/27. Given the duration and nature of the complaint, it is unlikely to represent a seizure.   Reading attending:
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This is a normal long term video EEG. There are no clinical or electrographic events reported or detected.
